AU  - Berndt, Ernst R.
AU  - Morrison, Catherine J.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 65
IS  - 1
SP  - 9
EP  - 43
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(94)01596-R
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769401596R
KW  - Information technology
KW  - Economic performance
KW  - Productivity
AB  - To what extent have investments in ‘high-tech’ office and information technology capital ‘delivered’ in terms of reducing costs and facilitating productivity growth? In this paper we explore relationships between industry performance measures and investments in high-tech office and information technology capital for two-digit manufacturing industries from 1968 through 1986. We find limited evidence of a positive relationship between profitability and the share of high-tech capital in the total physical capital stock (OFK). However, we find that increases in OFK are negatively correlated with multi-factor productivity and tend to be labor-using. We also find some evidence that industries with a higher proportion of high-tech capital have higher measures of economic performance, although within industries increasing OFK does not appear to improve economic performance.
